Admittedly, I burst out laughing when I first read the title of the article. Then I read that they stayed open after health inspectors cited them... lines out the door of unsuspecting customers waiting to drop serious cash on mouse dropping infused croissants, glazed with mouse urine. Awesome. The report from Friday noted "mice droppings throughout facility along floors/walls primarily in the rear prep room, as well as droppings on top of bags of flour." "The bakery underwent two separate inspections on Nov. 19 and 22, before the closure was enacted Friday, according to inspection reports obtained by SFGATE. The restaurant was given an opportunity to correct the violations during the initial inspection on Nov. 19. The license was later suspended due to a "severe mice infestation" during a routine re-inspection Friday, the report stated"

Tasty baked goods in a quaint cafe setting. I visited Tartine on a rainy weekday morning, which I think helped me beat the crowd. The line was pretty short when I got there. I ordered a morning bun, the quiche, and a cup of cold brew. The morning bun was delicious! Flaky, buttery, perfect balance of citrus to sweetness. The quiche was aiiiiiite. The crust was kind of hard so it was difficult to eat. I stuck to the egg part. I'd go back for the morning bun though.

It is very hard to find a place with baked goods, even if I'm willing to pay a lot for it. As much as I hate waiting in a long line to get baked goods from Tartine, I must admit that this bakery is truly amazing. The chef must bake their pastries and deserts with lots of love and passion. I don't come here often. I will drive into the city for Tartine sweet treats, only when my cravings get serious! Highly recommend to get 1. The banana cream pie- and I don't even like eating bananas. The crust is incredible! 2. The morning buns 3. Almond cream tart 4. Blueberry tart 5. Brioche pudding 6. Chocolate croissants are a good option if you don't like any of those above. This place is a bit pricey. I don't like the long line and the crowd. However, this place totally deserves my five solid stars.

I honestly have no idea why Tartine has only 4 stars. Maybe it's because the lines are long or the pastries aren't the best (they're great - but not worth the line in my opinion). I'm also not sure it's the best place for a quick bite, given the crowds. That said, I don't come to Tartine for the pastries - I come for the bread. I first found out about Tartine loooooooong before I moved to SF; I actually learned about it when I was experimenting with alternative diets back in 2011. I do eat wheat, but one thing that fascinated me about Tartine is that the baker's wife is gluten-intolerant, but can eat his bread. The bread is fermented much longer than normal "quick yeast" breads, which makes the wheat easier to digest - AND more flavorful (I also read they experiment with different grains). I'm honestly not sure about any of the science behind it, but I do have to say the final product is absolutely delicious. The bread is better than any I had - even in Paris. I usually get the porridge loaf. Hook that up with some cheese (Bi-Rite is next door, but I often just go to Trader Joe's on the way home in SoMa), and you have a meal TO DIE FOR. I've always visited later in the day and never had any problems with things running out. The loaves are always fresh and warm, with the perfect balance of a crusty exterior and airy interior. The pastries I've had? Banana cream tart (solid), croissant (great - better than B Patisserie), walnut brownie (nice, but I prefer Recchiuti's). They're very good - but I do live with a baker, so I'm generally not impressed unless the pastries are significantly better. After all, why trek out to the Mission when you can eat pastries from your living room couch? That said, I'm thankful I don't live in the Mission or I'd be 10 pounds heavier with Tartine nearby.

The croque monsieur was perfection, so no complaints there, but the chocolate croissant obliterated into a bazillion papery shards--and not in a good way--the second we tried to take a bite of it. It was overdone and just not that good. The morning bun was fine, but not so special and the lemon tart wasn't quite set enough (though delicious)

    Service was what you'd expect chez Mission hipster and coffees were great. Dunno if it's us or them or what, but...4 stars. That said, Tartine will still be a must pitstop whenever we're in the bay area.

  • Jamie K.
    Lomita, CA
